Rating: 4
Everyone loved it. It does take a long time to make, especially the cream topping. It says to stir occasionally....I would say every 2 minutes at least. The milk cuts if you aren't careful.....mine took a little longer to bake after putting the mushrooms and cream. My crust came out perfect. I think because of sheer luck. But what I did was bake it the first 2 times at 350 instead of 375 (it may depend on your oven. The 3rd time I did do it at 375. Came out wonderful!!!!

Rating: 4
Excellent recipe! I added asparagus to the mushrooms & it complimented the dish well. The crust is very good, but mine was a bit too soft. Next time I will bake it longer, before adding the toppings. I also added freshly grated parm. regiano to the top right before baking. Looking forward to making this great recipe again!

Rating: 3
This dish has become one of our standards. It's so versatile--wonderful for dinner with a simple green salad, a terrific accompaniment to roast meats, the perfect brunch entree--and so simple. This is the recipe most frequently requested by our guests. What did we do without it? The only change we sometimes make is to use an herbed chevre--makes an already great dish even better. Enjoy!

Rating: 4
This is a wonderful recipe! I was very short on time and so I used Pillsbury pie crust sheets which fit perfectly into a tart pan and are really quite good. I used a mixture of mushrooms and asparagus, but I imagine you can use almost anything you like in this tart. The goat cheese spread on the bottom definitely makes a statement without being overpowering, such as in Herb and Goat Cheese Tart (Gourmet, July 1997). Garnish the dish and you have a very nice first course.

